<html>
<body>

<center>
<b>TRANSFER RINEX METEO FILES TO BERNESE FORMAT</b>
<p>Program: RXMBV3
</center>
<hr width="100%">

<a name="ENVIRONMENT"   default="%% %%"></a>
<a name="CAMPAIGN"      default=""></a>
<a name="SESSION_TABLE" default="SESSIONS"></a>
<a name="YR4_INFO"      default="$Y+0"></a>
<a name="SES_INFO"      default="$S+0"></a>
<a name="USR_INFO"      default="${USER}"></a>

<p><b>GENERAL DESCRIPTION</b>
<p>
Use this program to transfer RINEX meteorological files into the Bernese
meteo file format.

<p><hr>

<p><b>RXMBV3 1: Input/Output Files</b>

<a name="SHOWGEN" default="1"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL FILES</b>
<p><b>Show all general files:</b>
If you check this box, the currently active campaign, session and session
table are displayed.

<br><br>

<a name="OBSFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>INPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>RINEX meteo file(s):</b>
Select RINEX meteorological files to
be imported into Bernese meteo file format. More than one file may be
selected per program run, but only files of <i>one</i> site may be combined
in the same run.
<br>
The input files have the
default extension <tt>yyM</tt> where yy is the two digit year of the default
session. Select the default session in the dialogue
<a href="SETDATE.HLP">Menu &gt; Configure &gt; Set session/compute day</a>.

<br><br>

<a name="NEWOLD" default="APPEND"></a>
<a name="METEON" default=""></a>
<a name="METEOA" default=""></a>
<p><b>RESULT FILES</b>
<p><b>NEW/APPEND</b> <b>Bernese meteo file:</b>
You may either append the RINEX meteo data
to an already existing Bernese meteo file (<b>APPEND</b>) or create a new
Bernese meteo file (<b>NEW</b>).
<ul>
<li><b>NEW:</b> Enter the Bernese meteo output filename if you
    have selected <b>NEW</b>. An empty input field means that
    the name of the first RINEX meteo file will be used as output name.
    <br>
    <i>Caution:</i> Existing files with the same name will be overwritten.
<li><b>APPEND:</b>
    Enter the Bernese meteo output filename where the
    meteo data should be appended if you have selected <b>APPEND</b>.
    <br>
    <i>Remark:</i> The file with the specified name has to already exist.
</ul>

<br>

<a name="SYSODEF" default="1"></a>
<a name="SYSOUT"  default="RXMBV3"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL OUTPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Program output:</b>
You can choose to have the program output written to a separate file for each
program run (checkbox marked), or specify a common name for all program runs.
<br>
If you mark the checkbox, the filename will correspond to the program name
with an extension containing a counter (Lnn), which is automatically
incremented for each program run. If the counter reaches the maximum value, it
is automatically reset, and existing files will be overwritten.
The maximum value can be set in
<b>Menu &gt; Configure &gt; Program Names</b>, option "Maximum program output
file number".
<br>
If the checkbox is unmarked, you have to specify a name for the program
output file. This allows to characterize the program run, e.g., by using the
day and year (<tt>$YD+0</tt>) in the filename.

<a name="ERRMRG" default="0"></a>
<a name="SYSERR" default="ERROR"></a>
<p><b>Error messages:</b>
You can choose to have error messages written into the program's output
file (see above), or specify a separate file to which error messages are
written.

<p><hr>

<p><b>RXMBV3 2: Station Name Translation</b>

<a name="TITLE" default=""></a>
<p><b>TITLE</b>
<p>
This title line will be printed as header comment into the program output
and will be saved in all the result files to document the program run.
The title should characterize the program run by, e.g., giving the most
important options used and the session.

<br><br>

<a name="STAINFO" default=""></a>
<p><b>STATION NAME TRANSLATION</b>
<p><b>Station information file:</b>
In this input field you may supply the name of a station information
file. The first section (<tt>TYPE001: Station renaming</tt>) will then be used
to translate the marker names in the RINEX meteo files before being
written to the Bernese meteo file. With <i>blank</i> no translation takes
place and the site name given in the RINEX file(s) will be used also
in the Bernese format.

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.STA">Example</a>

<!-- This panel will not be displayed
<a name="USEFLG" default="0"></a>
<a name="FLG001" default="999"></a>
<p><b>Flags to be used</b>
Specify the flags used from the first section (TYPE 001: Station renaming)
of the station information file for this program run. Select the flag
<tt>999</tt> activate all entries from this section of the station problem
file.
-->

<a name="STNMSTOP" default="0"></a>
<p><b>Stop if station name not found: </b>
This option defines whether the program should stop if the station in
the RINEX file is not present in the station name translation table or
whether it should continue, just using the RINEX station name without
translation.

<p><hr>

</body>
</html>
